segments.text: And these are local Chinese artists who come on and perform for you at the base occasionally.
And subsequently, when we got in combat, of course, the mayor would come out and give us special honors.
On one occasion, the first fight we had where we repulsed an enemy attack of 14 bombers,
from hitting Kunming.
We turned them around before they ever got to the city.
And of course, the city heard about that.
And they came out the following about two days after.
It was a great party.
And the Generalissimo sent one of his emissaries up and wrapped a, he, each one of us got a, it was a sort of a red scarf, which
mean something to them in China.
I still don't know what it means, but it's something very dear, and it's a great honor to get a red scarf, and gave each one of the pilots one of these.
Subsequently, of course, some of us got medals.
The Chinese military, oh, man, they just, they were particularly Chinese, what, reminiscent of the Chinese Air Force.
They just loved us.
We never...
We flew a few missions toward the latter part of our tour.
Let's say around April or May of 43, the Chinese manned Russian bombers.
There was about 15, 20 old Russian light bombers from the Chinese crew.
And we'd escort them.
Many times, we'd have to navigate them to the target.
Otherwise, they'd never got there.
In one case, we did this on Hanoi.
See, that was Japanese occupied.
Yeah, I know.
We'll get to that.
Now, did Chiang Kai-shek ever, did he ever come down and talk to you?
Did you ever get a chance to meet him?
Chiang Kai-shek visited Steele one time, and then I say this with hindsight now.
Chiang Kai-shek was
no more than one of the biggest dictators in China.
At the time, of course, he was in a deadlock fight with Mao Zedong and the communists.
That didn't mean much to me in those days.
I never even thought of such things as that.
To me, he was China.
Chiang Kai-shek and Oman were China.
And we had a great deal of respect for them.
And he visited us at the field one day.
Of course, we had to go to Chennault.
But I happened to be up around headquarters in Atlanta.
He got out of an old Goonie Bird.

DC-3, but before he stepped out, at least five or ten so-called Secret Service people, if you will, in Chinese uniforms, with pistols drawn out in their hand, pulled out of their holsters at ready, stepped off the airplane and then gathered around a circle, and then the generalissimo got off.
He always wore his uniform.
Every time I saw him, he wore his uniform, and got off.
Of course, I just happened to see him then.
I have never spoken personally to Gisimo.
I never did speak to him personally.
I've seen him at banquets, and I've been maybe 10 or 15 feet from him, but I've never spoken to him personally or shook hands with him.
Madam, I have.
I've talked with her in conversation.
Very charming person.
Tell me, what were your opinions of both of these people?
Well, my opinion of Gisimo was strictly from...
stories I'd heard of him from two or three times I saw him at a short distance, and from his pictures.
I'm stating my opinion strictly based on mostly from what I read and understood and picked up from some people who were authoritative and some who were not.
He definitely was the biggest, one of the biggest warlords of China.
And of course, marrying a madam, he married money.
She was related to the Soom family.
And so with his power, military power, and authority, and her money, he was the number one man.
From stories I heard, he was very capable in dealing with foreigners.
over the bargaining table, a la Len Leith.
He was a good strategist.
He was definitely, definitely a military man.
He was much more of a strategist on the planet than he was a tactician.
How good an administrator he was, I don't know.
His wife... Did Chennault ever say anything about him?
These are some of the stories that I...
The reason I say based on stories I've heard, Chennault had a fantastic respect for him, but I think
The main reason Chennault had a fantastic respect for him is because, in effect, he was the Generalissimo's number one air power advisor.
Very close to him.
And vice versa.
Seeing the capabilities Chennault had, the Generalissimo had a great respect for him.
So there was a terrific mutual respect between the two of them.
I'm sure Chennault thought he was a great man.
I don't know enough about him to say yes or no.
He was an impressive person.
If I would say at a bargaining table, I would say that the madam could get as much as he could.
She was very charming and very capable and could speak English well enough.
Very good, as a matter of fact.
And she was very influential with President Roosevelt.
So was the Generalissimo.

As a matter of fact, in subsequent head-to-head fights, if you will, over who was going to control the AVG, which was eventually coming in the Air Force, Chenault always had the Generalissimo behind him, vis-a-vis Hap Arnold.
In other words, Hap Arnold wanted it.
Oh, yes.
And Chenault wanted it, too.
Hap Arnold and Chenault hated each other's guts, period.
and they fought like cats and dogs.
Of course, as many things are, he was compromised, and Chenault was given his reserve commission back in the Air Force and made a Brigadier General and ultimately a two-star general and three stars.
And of course, when he was given this title, of course, he was also commander of the
newly established 14th Air Force, which was in China, per se, and which also took the old emblem of the Flying Tigers.
That's where you always see the Flying Tigers at the 14th Air Force.
Now, did you ever hear anything about Mao Zedong or ever have any thoughts about him whatsoever while you were there?
I've thought about that a lot.
since, and knowing as much about it as I do now, and watching history unfold, I don't ever recall hearing Mao Zedong.
It seems that I do recall bits of discussion about so-called red Chinese communists.
And I do know that I remember stories of, you know, there'd be convoys of trucks coming up the Burmese trail from,
Rangoon to Kunming, and eventually on up to Chongqing.

But there were many stories, and I'm sure this is true, subsequently I've heard stories that proved to be true, that in these convoys, as the convoys would get over into China from Burma across the border, maybe every third or fourth, maybe have it flat and drop out,
convoy and had to fix it, and then he'd never show up.
He'd turn off and go back up the hills, and that truck load of arms, maybe if you will, like rifles and stuff, would eventually trickle into Mount Titone.
And some of this was just pure fraud and sabotage, if you will, the Chinese getting his cover shot, in other words, getting his tips, which is typical of the Far East.
I saw that in Thailand later on, by the way.
And so it might have been Mao, and it might not have been Mao.
A lot of land lease equipment, I am sure, went to Mao Zedong.
I'm sure of that.
Or it might have gone to another warlord?
No, it had to be either Generalissimo or Mao Zedong, one of the two.
But you never really heard much about him, except you heard about the Red Chinese.
OK.
So much for Mao.
Let's move to regulations.
said before that there was a club, but it wasn't an officer's club, it wasn't an enlisted club.
What was the relationship between the men who had been former sergeants or enlisted men and the ones who had been former officers?
Were they all treated as equal first-man bases or what?
We had two hostels in Kunming.
The big one in town proper, away from the field, was really the AVG headquarters, where General Chernoff lived.
There were dormitories there for officers, well, pilots, if you will, and the maintenance people, airmen, if you will.
They lived together and had the same aid together.
Over in our hostel at the, where my particular squad, the first of the pilots were in one hostel, the maintenance men were in the other.
They were all in the same house.
And my hostel, which was right on the field proper, practically on the field, adjacent to the field, but the first squadron hostel, if you will.
We had our club.
We had our mess, where the airmen and the officers, polished so-called, got together.
Now, because all of us were recruited military people, and if you will, experienced military people, most of us,
We had it ingrained in us a little bit about the aloofness between officers and airmen.
So we didn't mix as freely as you would think.
For instance, getting an officer in the club, the airmen, 95% of them mostly, would get over in their corner and have their drinks in discussion, whereas the pilots get over in the other corner.
Even when you sat down to eat, it'd be more or less like this.
But there was no specific requirement saying we had to be separated.
We just sort of followed what was traditional in military units.
As time went on, this characteristic sort of mellowed into one where we mixed much more freely and had poker games together.
And I've even seen the pilots and the airmen getting in fights and jugging melees together.
it mattered towards you, particularly when we got in combat.
And did the enlisted men call the pilots, sir?
No, none of that.
Matter of fact, at times I got worried about what would happen with our discipline, you know.
Yeah, I love that.
I got worried about, well, now, are we going to turn into one of these so-called mercenary outfits where we just go to hell?
I got a little concerned at times.
I'd have discussions with Chenault.
I had personally had discussions with Chenault about this, and he wasn't worried about it.
He appreciated my interest in it, but he says, I think you're overworked.
I don't think it's a good thing.
When we get in combat, you'll see all these problems disappear.
You won't hear any of this bitching and crap.
And he was so right.
He was.
Yes, sir.
A outfit that's not doing anything, that's not busily engaged, is apt to get into trouble.
The old story you heard, you know,
For instance, guys sit over in the corner and vote and worry about him, but the guys all around bitch and don't worry about him.
When we were heavily involved in training in the earlier days at Canggu, we didn't have any great problems, but there was no comparison when we got to combat.
There was no problem at all.
It's hard for a person to believe
that you throw a bunch of people like this together and see them or hear about them operating so efficiently and smoothly as we did in our combat operations when we got involved in combat.
I brought my airplane down plenty of holes and bullet holes.
The next day, boy, at 7 o'clock when I went out there to get that airplane, rev up the engine and get it ready, give it a pre-flight check, those holes were patched.
overnight and done well.
So those maintenance men were really part of the team.
That's right, and they were backed up by these Chinese coolies that could do the menial and hard labor.
But remember now, we had the elite of the airmen.
For instance, we'd have something wrong with the engine wouldn't be running right.
My maintenance man would take
my carburetor off that engine, and in no time flat he'd have it completely spread all over the bench, you know, tear it to pieces.
It's unheard of.
And the Red Ground fit me on the States Air Force.
But, you know, no 1st or 2nd National Line maintenance, all that stuff, you know.
He'd have to take it apart to find what's wrong with it, put it back together, and make it go ahead and run it beautifully.
It's just an outstanding mechanic.
Right.
He was trained.
And some things, you know, born out of necessity, you learn to fix.
Now, admit, some of our parts on the airplane were probably put together with, let's say, maybe a brass boat rather than a steel boat, but, you know, it's held together, that type of thing.
But I often think back, and as a matter of fact, some of my buddies get together maybe at a reunion, and
How in the hell did we do that?
But we did it.
I have.
So there's no breakdown in it.
No.
Discipline whatsoever.
No.
Well, no.
Really, the answer is no.
You can't think of any?
No.
Oh, there's some little instance.
Oh, yeah.
Matter of fact, Peppy Boynton, Greg Boynton, Black Sheep Boy.
No.
Was he?
Pappy was in my squadron.
I know him very well.
Oh, really?
I'm probably one of the very few guys in AVG, Flying Tigers, that Pappy Boynton never got in a fight with.
Really?
Pappy tried his best at times to get me in a fight.
And it might very well be that that's the reason I'm living today, because he was quite a big boy, but not that I was afraid of him.
As a matter of fact, I have.
on top of Pappy Boynton, holding him down in a grump and stupor.
And Pappy and I today are the closest friends.
Where does he live now?
I think he's out in California.
I think California.
But anyway, tell me, he was just a pugnacious type?
Oh, very pugnacious.
Pappy's biggest, and he admitted it, was a bottle.
Matter of fact, that's where he left the Marine Corps.
He knew he might as well.
He was a terrific man as an individual.
a terrific pilot as an individual.
But as a flight leader over there, he lost several of the airplanes by lack of navigation or something.
He just never did get off on the right foot in Flying Tigers, and mainly because he arrived drinking and stayed drinking.
As a matter of fact, he was dishonored and discharged from the Flying Tigers, you know.
And he left China
on a Air Transport, United States Air Force Air Transport Command B-24 when he wasn't supposed to, and the pilot that took him out didn't know it.
But Chenault had put out strict orders when he was drawn back into the Air Force.
Under no conditions will an Air Force aircraft take this man out of China.
He was getting ready for it.
This is not well-known, but it's true.
But subsequently, old Pappy, you know, went back home, got back in the Marine Corps, and did a, well, he got the Medal of Honor.
Mm-hmm.
He's a pretty combat man, but he's like some of those typical people.
In time of war, you've got to have them, but in time of peace, what are you doing?
A la Patton, a la some of the other people.
Yeah, that's the best example.
But he does want to pick a fight with them.
That's always when he's tight.
Sure.
But I still think that he was a good man.
He just didn't get along well over there.
He got up on the wrong foot.
But Chenault had the, he could discharge people.
I mean, what, you mean he'd just fire you?
Because you were not in a military unit, per se.
Oh, yeah, he fired them.
He just fired you.
He didn't discharge you.
Well.
How could he give you dishonor?
Well, you see, I'm talking about times after.
This was after the ABG was.
Okay, part of the U.S. Army.
Chenault was inducted back into the service before the ABG was disbanded.
Well, yeah, he came back, he was, Chenault had just got inducted back into service probably, I'd say in April or May of 1942.
Whereas we officially weren't disbanded, officially disbanded until July the 4th, 1942.
And then- And a lot of us, several of us, that's another story, several of us stayed over until the 10th of July.
Very, very hard aerial combat down here.
We're going to get to that.
We want to get back to the regulations, though.
Now, we've talked about the relationships between the former officers and the former enlisted men.
What about the uniforms?
The only thing we had in the way of uniforms that resembled military was those parts of, let's say, our military clothing.
that when we got out of the service, we took with us because we know we could use.
For instance, my flying coveralls.
I had a blouse that I had a military blouse, the old what we called pinks in the military at that time, or the Army, Army Air Corps.
It's sort of a gray slacks with a OD tunic.
We called them pinks.
Well, I had those copied in a sort of a gray, summertime uniform type, if you will, by a Chinese tailor.
It looked just like, but a different color.
What I chose to have as my uniform.
Most of us did follow the British jungle khaki type.
The British jungle blouse was slacks, and then shorts in the summertime.
I've seen guys in an airplane in combat wearing straw hats, big cowboy type straw hats with earphones over them.
I've seen them in t-shirts.
We didn't have any particular uniforms.
There were no uniform regulations at all, per se, no uniform regulations.
Did you like or dislike them?
I didn't mind.
It didn't bother me.
The only thing that struck me sometimes is a regulation pertaining, let's say, to discipline or control of people, like you can or can't do this.
There's very, very few regulations.
Oh, you'd see something on a bulletin board in a bar, for instance, you can't take drinks after midnight or something like that outside, something like that.
But there was a minimum of regulation.
Now, of course, we had the regular tech orders for the airplane.
Just like those that are furnished with any airplane to the Air Force.
And maintenance of the equipment.
Standing orders for maintenance, of course.
Right.
Now, to log a flight, log a time, we had a forms one, those types.
You just practically had to keep records.
We'd have those.
But like the DASH regulations for personnel, the DASH series for the district, the DASH series for the medical supplies, paperwork was a minimum, absolute minimum.
What about as far as an identification card?
Did you have any ID card?
Of course, each one of us had our ID.
passport with a visa in it.
Under your own name.
Yeah, under my own name.
Like I was Charles R. Bond Jr.
Clerk.
It's not clerk.
Yeah, it's clerk.
But now, if I remember correct, yeah, we kept those in possession all the time.
Even when you flew?
No, not in combat.
But likely, if we go from, move the unit from China down to Burma, we'd take that with us in our luggage, you know, the passport.
So you'd have it with you.
Or when we'd go to India to ferry an airplane back, we'd take that with us.
I don't recall, oh, we'd have, no, matter of fact, to answer your question, we didn't have any official identification sites.
I don't recall any.
But we'd go down, have the printing office on one side make us like a business card, Charles Arbonne, ABG, then on the other side put Chinese letters, you know, Charles Arbonne.
What about if you were shot down?
And the Japanese got a hold of you.
Then what?
Again, it was just name, purpose on the unit.
Is that what Chennault told you?
No.
Now, when it comes to that type of thing, to the extent we had been trained for this, Chennault didn't figure he had to harp much on this.
That's still typical.
We were military outfit when it comes to that.
But now we did wear the...
I got a trunk out in the garage.
You don't need to see all this stuff.
You've seen pictures of it.
We wore it on the back of our jacket.
In effect, it was printed in Chinese.
It had a Chinese flag on it.
It printed on a Chinese flag, in effect.
And in effect, it said in Chinese, this is an American volunteer fighting for the Chinese.
Give him all assistance if you possibly can.
That's on the back of the jacket.
Yeah, that was on there.
We'd sew that on the back of the jacket.
But incidentally, the two times I was shot down, I didn't have equipment.
I didn't have my jacket on.
And what would you fly in?
No, I know, but what uniform?
What would you usually wear yourself?
Whenever I'd fly, I'd always wear my flying suit.
And eventually, when that got so bad, like I say, these 250 calibers,
sticking out in your cockpit.
You know, you had to keep them all.
And particularly when you're firing them, you know, they've got a pattern.
The oil would drop out.
It dropped right at your feet when your rudder's pedaled and your flying coveralls.
Flying coveralls always from knee down would just pull them all continually.
I'd have to watch them every day, you know.
But eventually, they just wore out.
Then we did have, finally got in supply,
It seemed like the only supplies we got, clothing, was always Navy.
I don't remember any Air Force stuff ever coming up.
But we began to, towards the end, you know, when we proved our value as a fighting outfit, and Lend-Lease began to take effect, we did get some or another, most of it was Navy supplies.
I got the Navy flying jacket, terrific one, that fur collar.
Then I wore a Navy flying suit all the time.
I had an old Air Force helmet when I was shot down the first time.
I always wore a helmet, of course, and an oxygen mask.
And gloves, half the time I'd wear my gloves.
The time I got shot down, I didn't have them on, big and stuff.
Boots, I had the calf-length boots that I wore all the time.
I had them made in India.
No, I had them made in Burma before I went up to China.
OK. Now, let's talk now for a minute about Chanel.
What kind of person was he?
Well, the first thing that impresses you about Chenault is the appearance of his face when you see him.
He's got that, in the typical picture you see him, he's got that jutted lower jaw stuck out, which indicates, you know, a determined, dogged individual.
He's that way.
that he is determined.
He's very hard of hearing.
Even back in 30, back in 41 when I first met him, he was very hard of hearing.
And to my knowledge, I never saw him wearing hearing aids.
He is, he talks softly.
He's got a good sense of humor.
He's got a wit about him.
He can needle you.
He is a tactician superb on flying airplanes.
He's much more, in my opinion, a tactician than he is a strategist.
What do you mean?
Tactical, in other words, like a fighter squadron.
But planning a war campaign, that I don't think was his sport.
Now, he learned it rapidly in planning campaigns in China because he had to.
He was the Air Force.
And he did well, but of course he had the backing of Generalissimo and all of his Chinese veteran
been in the Army all their lives and knew the country and all.
General Chenault didn't have a complete Air Force.
He didn't have a bomber force.
He just had fighters and some training aircraft.
He knew how to organize and get a unit going.
Did he win the respect of his men?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Matter of fact, all of us loved him.
Well, it was lovely.
There was no dissension?
Oh, yes.
There was a few.
There's always a few, you know.
I've heard Greg Boyden get mad at him.
I actually got mad at you, old man.
When I was down in Burma, you know, with Bob Neal.
Bob Neal was the squadron commander and I was his assistant.
I always refer to Bob Neal and I because eventually, if you will, he was a group commander and I was a group assistant.
I was a group operations officer, if you will.
practically the whole outfit.
But when we were down in Burma, remote from him up in China, we were on our last bottle of oxygen, and there was no effort to get us any more.
Well, what the hell's the old man thinking about?
We can't fly like this.
Well, I guess everybody makes comments about their boss.
He probably knew the situation, but just had no oxygen to get us.
I don't ever remember the old man making a
a decision that I was absolutely against.
He personally ordered me to take some flights, which I did, and I should have.
A couple of them I couldn't perform, and I had to return because of weather.
I had to relieve another outfit.
It was battle ridden, and I couldn't.
But he knew as well as I did that when I returned, I brought the other eight airplanes back with me.
He was disappointed, and I knew it, but he never held it against me.
He'd been the first to congratulate me when I returned from shooting an airplane down.
He always seemed to show up at critical times when his presence was felt as a morale booster.
He could talk to you where you could understand him.
I've seen him stand up, you know, when morale was getting a little low.
For instance, we up at Kunming, sitting there not in fights, you know, for a while, early part of 42, and the third squad down in Rangoon was fighting every day, you know.
Not just because of the $500 an airplane never getting shot when they shoot them down, but we just weren't in combat, and damn it, we wanted to go down there.
Well, he had to explain why he couldn't rotate us as quick and as often as we wanted to, because...
And he'd get up, and some of the men were disgruntled, apologizing.
He would stand up and talk to them just like I'm talking to you, not as a commander talking to his men, but not as a general talking to a private, but as a man talking to a man.
And he had savvy feelings.
He could explain things away.
A motivator.
But he wouldn't, I don't think he would inspire me.
He would, I would do what he wanted me to do, and did.
I respect him, but for instance, I didn't have almost the reverence for him like I had for LeMay.
I knew LeMay was, I just knew he was a great man going to be.
Chenault, he's my boss.
I trust him, and I'll fight for him.
He's that different.
But you had confidence in this man and you trusted him?
Oh, yeah, definitely.
When he told you something, that was the way it was?
I mean, he was an honest person?
Oh, absolutely.
And he had his troubles at his level, you know, for instance, retaining his command.
Even before he was inducted back in service, they had two or three...
Air Force Brigadier General in India in the 10th Air Force.
Fighter-type commanders, you know, were just dying and pulling every string they could back to half-Arnold to come over and take over that Flying Tiger Group.
And the old man always had to go to the Generalissimo, the old man Chennault, and of course stop anything like that.
No, he was a General Chennault, in my opinion,
But what that man did, not only for the United States and for China, but for the world at that time, he deserves, in my opinion, to be one of the great men of history.
I don't think he's ever gotten full credit for what he did.
No, he didn't.
But looking back now, if you recall, well, you don't recall because you weren't born then, but this was in 41 and 42.
The darkest, well, Pearl Harbor Day in a few weeks and months, right after Pearl Harbor Day, December 7, 1941.
Boy, there were some dark days in this country.
Oh, I studied it.
Oh, well, and you studied it.
Okay.
But, I mean, if you'd lived it.
Yeah.
See, I've talked to her wife and my mother and father and them, you know.
And, boy, this country was, they were worried, scared.
And the only bright spot,
across the entire worldwide horizon, not only in Japan, but in Europe.
Nobody would win in Europe in war.
We hadn't even gotten into it.
Was the American Volunteer Group going to combat and shoot down 24 airplanes, about losing one.
Eight airplanes against 60.
I've been in combat with 14 of us against probably 125.
be shot down.
Well, we're going to get to that.
But to answer your question, he did something for the country in the darkest days that helped us over the bumpy spots.
And a lot of his criticism comes from petty jealousy, in my opinion, by his professional rivals.
You follow me?
Sure.
I wanted to ask you, what about his leadership capability?
Well, I think I expressed that he was, no doubt, he was a leader.
Now, he didn't fly with us.
No.
See, in the earlier days when he was in China, he actually flew an airplane and actually fought some of the Japs.
I'm told this.
I don't know this for a fact, but I'm sure I believe it.
But with us, that was not his job.
He didn't fly with us.
He had his own little troop.
his own little personal airplane, if you will call it, a little transport, that he picked, by the way, one of the Navy pilots, picked one of him, the Navy pilots out, to fly it for him.
And he, if there was a problem at some particular base because of supply or something that was a difficult problem, lack of supply or organization, something communicated broke down, he'd show up.
He'd show up at critical times.

When we were starting a new campaign, let's say when we were moving a unit, like we moved from one base to another and sort of move in late at night with the idea of the next day catching a raid that came up habitually every day at, say, 10 o'clock in the morning, a la training purpose for the Japanese Air Force out of Hanoi against Kuilin.
He'd come there and be on hand.
Whenever he was at our base, we knew something was going to happen.
He was that dynamic.
Yet, I say that dynamic.
Yet, I would never call him a dynamic person.
Why not?
Well, you think of a dynamic person as somebody entering the room, and he just bursts in and takes over.
And boy, you know he's there.
If you'd not have come into the room, you'd see him.
He'd start telling you what he was there for, and sort of on a controlled basis, he'd take over and things would proceed without any great hullabaloo and so forth.
He was much more mild mannered.
More mild mannered?
Yes, more mild mannered.
But I've seen him mad where he cussed like Patton does, supposedly did.
Now, let's get to your, what exactly was your title, and exactly what was your job during these combat missions, during 1942?
During 1942?
Well, I was a wingman.
I was inducted as a wingman in the American Voluntary Group, and I eventually was supported.
I was appointed to a flight leader, probably the early part of
to a flight leader as a result of the December 18th air battle, the first one we had.

Then I was a flight leader, and I turned out to be, you might say, the operations officer, if you will, for our first pursuit squadron, and Bob Neal was squadron commander's right-hand man after Sandell, the original squadron commander, was killed.
Okay, and how many in the squadron?
I'd have to refer to my records for the exact number.
We originally planned to have 25 airplanes, 25 pilots.

Half of that.
Normally, most of our emergency were air defense nature, taking off from alert.
Sometimes we'd have an air cap flying around, being prepared in the air for interception of the enemy, expecting to come over.
But normally we'd operate and always take off in pairs, never by ourselves.
At least two airplanes.
Well, for instance, it depends on the situation.
At Rangoon, we had cross runways, and we had four airplanes dispersed at the end of each of the two crossing runways, a total of eight.
At other places, we had only two airplanes on alert, which is common practice, ground alert, and both of them would take off together.
Whenever we planned a mission, like we planned the attack on Chiang Mai Air Base in Thailand in March 1942, we planned that with 12 airplanes.
The most airplanes that have ever been in combat together on our side, the most airplanes that the flying Tigers ever put up in one fight was 14.
at one time in Kunming, and I think we dispersed a flight of bombers at that time.
Most of the nine-tenths of my fighting, 85% of it, was done in Rangoon, where normally we'd put up anywhere from, every plane we could get up there, we'd have ready, you know, to get in a fight.
But we knew, I fought as many as four times a day, beat the enemy actually four times one day.
Normally we'd have about eight to twelve, and maybe there'd be four RAF boosters or hurricanes that had come to evacuate out of Singapore.
Normally we'd have eight to twelve.
We had twelve up, that was good.
Many times we've taken over two airplanes.
But I'd see as many as 120, 125, 130 Japanese fighters come over against us, and we'd have eight airplanes there.
Now, how long did you stay out of Kunming?
Well, right after Pearl Harbor Day, two of the squadrons went up to Kunming.
On the 14th of December, one went to Rangoon.
We continued to stay in that posture.
Rotating every now and about once every month or 35 days, changing the squadron at Rangoon back up to Kunming and replacing it with one of the old squadrons down there.
So we kept one fourth, one third of the outfit at Rangoon until the British forced us out the last day or two of February 1942.
And that happened to be our squadron.
And then they took over.
And they took over.

Northern Burma.

about four to eight airplanes down there with the RAF and helping them still defend at least northern part of Burma for about a month.
Then we pulled out of there back further north and last you'll see the Japanese begin to penetrate further north into Burma and eventually we pulled everything across into
Low Wing China, which is just across the river into southern Yunnan province of China.
Pulled completely out of Burma because the Japanese were then approaching the southern border of China.
And we continued to operate out of Low Wing, which was really our main supply base in the southern part of China,
Burma Road had been built that far north at that time, and we had a supply base there.
And then we operated out of Lower Wing and Kunming against the Japanese in the Burma area for quite a while.
And later on, we moved toward the Kunming outskirts up to Chungking, then subsequently from Chungking to Guilin, depending on where the operations were the most critical.
But see, we had to defend the Burma Road approaches.
